Pantheon Universal Translator (PUT) Architecture v1.0

Subtitle: Representation-invariant transmutation engine for meaning-preserving translation across substrates

This is the system design that turns the doctrine into machinery.

It takes the Pantheon idea seriously:

meaning is not the file. not the syntax. not the medium.
Meaning is the load-bearing structure that survives transformation.

So the Universal Translator is not a converter farm.
It is a semantic extraction, normalization, and rehydration engine.

⸻

1. Mission

The Pantheon Universal Translator exists to:
	•	extract semantic invariants from any representation
	•	normalize them into a canonical intermediate form
	•	rehydrate them into another representation
	•	declare what was preserved, changed, or lost
	•	validate that the target artifact still carries the intended structure

Its operating law is:

Extract the invariant, change the vessel.

⸻

2. Core Thesis

Traditional systems do this:

format A → parser → format B

Pantheon does this:

representation A
  ↓
surface parse
  ↓
structure extraction
  ↓
invariant identification
  ↓
canonical meaning object
  ↓
target planning
  ↓
rehydration
  ↓
validation
  ↓
representation B

This is why it scales past file types into:
	•	docs
	•	code
	•	diagrams
	•	workflows
	•	stories
	•	schemas
	•	plans
	•	prompts
	•	interfaces
	•	operational procedures

